D7B5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub18.ezboard.com/utalanic.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Talanic</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>MithMarr Knight<BR><img src=http://pages.cthome.net/shellene/star.gif height=10 width=11 border=0><img src=http://pages.cthome.net/shellene/star.gif height=10 width=11 border=0></span><br>  Posts: 113<br> <font color=#330000>(5/13/02 10:32:22 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub18.ezboard.com/fmithanielmarrdailynewsfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1098.topic&index=21>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   ...</span><hr size=1> Estimation is useful for when you're not sure on what the exact answer will be, but man...it is a bad idea to put the correct answer on a multiple choice test about estimation.<br>
<br>
Estimation's supposed to be used on problems where you CAN'T find the right answer, like in some calculus problems.  It's technically impossible to get an EXACT integral due to the way that the problem goes; it's all estimated if you follow the problems exactly.  <br>
<br>
Schools teach estimation early because if kids never estimate until they start getting into Calculus it throws 'em for a loop.  But it sounds like that test was made by an idiot...<br>
<br>
Oh, and for evolution, the main point is that it is a THEORY.  Never, ever teach a Theory as a fact.  Teaching the theory of evolution as a fact not only is scientifically inaccurate until it can be proven, it's also likely to offend many people who pay taxes...and you know what that means.  Teaching it to preschoolers is a bigger mistake--they won't understand it at that age.<br>
<br>
